{
  "texts": [
    "Going back to the original distribution f (t, A, w) and still focusing on the controlled model, together with the assumptions G ≡ 1 and D(w) = √ 1 -w 2, if the initial distribution f in (A, w) has a compact support, Proposition 4 ensures that all agents become active in finite time.",
    "Therefore, starting from such finite time, the mass of f (t, A, w) with respect to A is concentrated in the interval (γ, +∞).",
    "Integrating the Fokker-Planck equation (27) for A ∈ (γ, +∞), we then infer that the marginal distributionh(t, w) = ∫ R f (t, A, w)dA, introduced in Subsection 2.4, is solution to ∂ t h(t, w) = σ 2 p 2 ∂ 2 w ((1 -w 2)h(t, w)) + λ p ∂ w (K[f](t, w) ∫ R ( Āω p + ε)f (t, A, w)dA) = σ 2 p 2 ∂ 2 w ((1 -w 2)h(t, w)) + λ p (ω p + ε) 2 ∂ w ((w -m in w)h(t, w)),(42)where m in w = m w (0) is the initial average opinion of the population, which is preserved over time since we are considering only agent-agent interactions.",
    "It is well-known that the adjoint equation of (42) corresponds to a Wright-Fisher-type model with constant coefficients, whose analytical properties have been investigated in several works, see e.g.",
    "In particular, its solution h(t, w) belongs to C ∞ (R + × (-1, 1)) and, close to the boundaries of I, behaves like the equilibrium of (42) given byh ∞ (w) = C(1 -w) -1+ (ωp+ε) 2 νp (1-m in w) (1 + w) -1+ (ωp+ε) 2 νp (1+m in w),(43)where C > 0 is a suitable normalization constant such that ∫ I h ∞ (w)dw = 1."
  ]
}